snippet.textDisplay: Trixie says Kentucky Kingdom (at that point in time, it was a Six Flags) being a biblical theme park, meanwhile as someone born and raised Louisville, Kentucky I know Six Flags Kentucky kingdom was a run of the mill theme park BUT WHAT FEW SEEM TO REMEMBER WAS THE VERY LARGE SECTION OF THE PARK DEVOTED TO LOONY TOONS. It’s all been rebranded now, it closed after that accident with the girl (the ride was the “Superman tower of power” and it was taken down shortly after the incident) and when it finally re-opened a few years ago it’s no longer a part of the “Six Flags” franchise and is known just as “Kentucky Kingdom” now.

snippet.textDisplay: Such a wonderful episode! And since trixie asked I thought I’d try to answer her question about frozen lakes. I just wanted to say the reason lakes don’t freeze all the way is because the surface of the water freezes first and that Ice and snow acts as insulation for the now “warmer” water beneath the surface so that water doesn’t freeze. If our winters were colder and longer eventually the lake would freeze completely, but because of their usual temp and duration the bottom of a lake usually remains unfrozen.
